{"pageProps":{"note":{"id":"f7m2c5b73rmo6b87s3e9zqa","title":"Heap Space","desc":"","updated":1713807661339,"created":1713683778613,"custom":{},"fname":"lang.java.jre.memory.heap","type":"note","vault":{"fsPath":".","selfContained":true,"name":"cs"},"contentHash":"fcf325807542befc094c544fdd77b366","links":[{"type":"wiki","from":{"fname":"lang.java.jre.memory.heap","id":"f7m2c5b73rmo6b87s3e9zqa","vaultName":"cs"},"value":"os.memory.ram.user.heap","position":{"start":{"line":2,"column":8,"offset":8},"end":{"line":2,"column":35,"offset":35},"indent":[]},"xvault":false,"sameFile":false,"to":{"fname":"os.memory.ram.user.heap"}},{"from":{"fname":"lang.java.jre.memory.lifecycle.objects","id":"f6lwf3ytkd2f80adq6eluvv","vaultName":"cs"},"type":"backlink","position":{"start":{"line":14,"column":30,"offset":378},"end":{"line":14,"column":59,"offset":407},"indent":[]},"value":"lang.java.jre.memory.heap"}],"anchors":{"how-is-object-stored-in-memory":{"type":"header","text":"How is object stored in memory?","value":"how-is-object-stored-in-memory","line":12,"column":0,"depth":2},"references":{"type":"header","text":"References","value":"references","line":21,"column":0,"depth":2}},"children":["u4exyxajoic7un1b1l4n317"],"parent":"amc2lep2ryay49km5b1v3y0","data":{}},"body":"<h1 id=\"heap-space\">Heap Space<a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading icon-link\" href=\"#heap-space\"></a></h1>\n<p>Java's <a href=\"/cs/notes/rcyl8thq38qrnmhzb4oheq6\">Heap Space</a> implementation.</p>\n<p>Used to allocate memory to objects at run time</p>\n<h2 id=\"how-is-object-stored-in-memory\">How is object stored in memory?<a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading icon-link\" href=\"#how-is-object-stored-in-memory\"></a></h2>\n<ul>\n<li>The actual data/structure that is stored on the heap starts with what's commonly called <em>object header</em>.</li>\n<li>Header contains — a (compressed) class pointer</li>\n<li>Class pointer —> an internal data structure</li>\n<li>Internal data structure — defines layout of the class</li>\n<li>Layout of class — stored in a separate memory area called Metaspace (or Compressed Class space if Compressed OOPs are used).</li>\n<li>The pointer can be 4 or 8 bytes, depending on the architecture - even on 64-bit systems, it's usually 4 bytes due to the Compressed OOPs optimization.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"references\">References<a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading icon-link\" href=\"#references\"></a></h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/61654407/how-references-are-stored-in-java\">How references are stored in Java</a></li>\n<li>More about layout of java objects — <a href=\"https://shipilev.net/jvm/objects-inside-out/\">Java Objects Inside Out</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wiki.openjdk.java.net/display/HotSpot/CompressedOops\">Compressed OOPs</a></li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<strong>Children</strong>\n<ol>\n<li><a href=\"/cs/notes/u4exyxajoic7un1b1l4n317\">Program Counter Register</a></li>\n</ol>\n<hr>\n<strong>Backlinks</strong>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"/cs/notes/f6lwf3ytkd2f80adq6eluvv\">Objects lifecycle in memory (cs)</a></li>\n</ul>","noteIndex":{"id":"7ncn3al6mmutkhgoesulce9","title":"Computer Science","desc":"","updated":1715103618849,"created":1713296516553,"custom":{"nav_order":0,"permalink":"/"},"fname":"root","type":"note","vault":{"fsPath":".","selfContained":true,"name":"cs"},"contentHash":"36faf26c6be438d4aed355d72b55a110","links":[{"type":"wiki","from":{"fname":"root","id":"7ncn3al6mmutkhgoesulce9","vaultName":"cs"},"value":"arch","position":{"start":{"line":6,"column":3,"offset":105},"end":{"line":6,"column":11,"offset":113},"indent":[]},"xvault":false,"sameFile":false,"to":{"fname":"arch"}},{"type":"wiki","from":{"fname":"root","id":"7ncn3al6mmutkhgoesulce9","vaultName":"cs"},"value":"paradigm","position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":3,"offset":159},"end":{"line":11,"column":15,"offset":171},"indent":[]},"xvault":false,"sameFile":false,"to":{"fname":"paradigm"}}],"anchors":{"references"